      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "82be8d0d-dc92-466c-805d-0e6f40c3ade5",
        "text": "Generally such firms prosper only in markets whose customers have extreme high technology needs, like certain prescription drugs or special chemicals, [[scientific instrument]]s, and [[safety-critical system]]s in medicine, [[aeronautics]] or [[military weapons]]. The extreme needs justify the high risk of failure and consequently high gross margins from 60% to 90% of revenues. That is, [[gross profit]]s will be as much as 90% of the sales cost, with manufacturing costing only 10% of the product price, because so many individual projects yield no exploitable product. Most industrial companies get 40% revenues only."
      },
